e-width="1"/></svg>
Autumn, 1973.

Soho, London.

You've written a book and you've a baby at home; tonight, somehow, you'll make them both make sense. The book took much longer to make than the little girl, but after an immediate, impromptu effort, you can't take much credit for her anyway.

She is born now and her mother, Aoife, sits at home, with the babe in her arms.

Home's cold; at home there is not enough food. If she's told you once, she's told you again that there's not enough money coming in. You're a good man so you've taken a job in a warehouse close by the flat. But you'll not make enough, not all year.

And so tonight, you've gone back to Soho, with a book in your bag and a sense of the place as it was, ten years ago, when &#42;no wife, no house or land still seemed quite natural.&#42;

You'll try, you suppose, the haunts you used to haunt and the people you knew. That'll work: it's a good book and God's a good man.

You've been thinking about the form of the aubade, the morning poem, the song of wake-me-not-so-I-might-have-my-dream. You've been thinking about the first love of your life; Lily, from the deepest valley in Wales.

<div style="text-align:center;"><span class="flash-reveal">Forget about your book, an aubade is a song to the dawn, and the only way out of Soho is to find one.</span></div>

<div style="text-align:center;margin-top:1.5em;">[[STEP INTO THE NIGHT|Dean Street]]</div>
</div>

:: The Spanish Artist {"position":"500,800","size":"100,100"}
<svg class="french-rule" viewBox="0 0 300 44" width="100%" height="44" preserveAspectRatio="none"><defs><linearGradient id="frAmb" x1="0" x2="1"><stop offset="0%" stop-color="#a06010" stop-opacity="0"/><stop offset="10%" stop-color="#b07020" stop-opacity="0.6"/><stop offset="50%" stop-color="#c88020" stop-opacity="0.72"/><stop offset="90%" stop-color="#b07020" stop-opacity="0.6"/><stop offset="100%" stop-color="#a06010" stop-opacity="0"/></linearGradient><linearGradient id="frLn" x1="0" x2="1"><stop offset="0%" stop-color="#c8a86a" stop-opacity="0"/><stop offset="10%" stop-color="#c8a86a" stop-opacity="0.95"/><stop offset="90%" stop-color="#c8a86a" stop-opacity="0.95"/><stop offset="100%" stop-color="#c8a86a" stop-opacity="0"/></linearGradient></defs><rect x="0" y="16" width="300" height="22" fill="url(#frAmb)"/><line x1="0" y1="16" x2="300" y2="16" stroke="url(#frLn)" stroke-width="2"/><line x1="0" y1="38" x2="300" y2="38" stroke="url(#frLn)" stroke-width="2"/><rect x="61" y="21" width="8" height="16" rx="1" fill="#002395"/><rect x="63" y="17" width="4" height="6" rx="1" fill="#002395"/><rect x="79" y="19" width="9" height="18" rx="1" fill="#f0f0f0"/><rect x="81" y="16" width="5" height="5" rx="1" fill="#f0f0f0"/><rect x="97" y="20" width="7" height="17" rx="1" fill="#ed2939"/><rect x="99" y="17" width="3" height="5" rx="1" fill="#ed2939"/><rect x="197" y="21" width="8" height="16" rx="1" fill="#002395"/><rect x="199" y="17" width="4" height="6" rx="1" fill="#002395"/><rect x="215" y="19" width="9" height="18" rx="1" fill="#f0f0f0"/><rect x="217" y="16" width="5" height="5" rx="1" fill="#f0f0f0"/><rect x="233" y="20" width="7" height="17" rx="1" fill="#ed2939"/><rect x="235" y="17" width="3" height="5" rx="1" fill="#ed2939"/><polygon points="150,20 155,27 150,34 145,27" fill="#c8a86a" opacity="0.8"/><polygon points="150,22 153,27 150,32 147,27" fill="#a06010" opacity="0.85"/></svg>

Benito de los Juncales del Este has a bottle of chablis, one-third-drunk, in his hand. He ushers you to a empty table, the one where the artists sat before they were too many, and all stood up to talk.

He has the eyes of a man who is happy to watch the light change.

He takes an empty glass from the table and pours.

'You're selling something,' he says. It's not a question. 'I can see it in the way you hold yourself. Like a man carrying a stone he cannot put down.'

He signals for two glasses of wine. The barman brings them without a word.

'I will tell you what I learned,' he says, 'from painting. You cannot force someone to see what you have made. You can only make it, and leave it where it might be found.'

He drinks.

'The work is yours. The seeing is theirs. Do not confuse the two, or you will go mad.'

[[He looks at you|The Painter's Gaze]]

